bug.short_desc: 'dnf erase kernel' still wants to remove the running kernel

long_desc.thetext:

Attached.
> The other question is whether the erase command should remove all > installonly packages or not just the oldest.
In the kernel case it should not remove the running kernel. The running kernel is most often the youngest kernel, but could be any of the other installed kernel, depending on what kernel the user started the system with.

Saw this on F22, checked on the F23 release live image and can reproduce it. Good news is that it's an illusion caused by the packaging structure, bad news is that the kernel package protection really isn't complete - the kernel-modules package for the running kernel can be removed.
The reason this happens is that "kernel" is an empty metapackage and the real kernel is in "kernel-core" - and that's what dnf detects as the running kernel and protects. So removing the kernel package corresponding to the running kernel is a completely harmless operation.
# dnf remove kernel Dependencies resolved. ============================================================================================================================= Package Arch Version Repository Size ============================================================================================================================= Removing: kernel x86_64 4.2.3-300.fc23 @System 0
Transaction Summary ============================================================================================================================= Remove 1 Package
Installed size: 0 Is this ok [y/N]: n Operation aborted. # rpm -ql kernel (contains no files)
Actually removing the running kernel is still forbidden though
# dnf remove kernel-core Dependencies resolved. Error: The operation would result in removing the booted kernel: kernel-core-4.2.3-300.fc23.x86_64. # rpm -ql kernel-core | wc -l 2145 # rpm -qf /boot/vmlinuz-4.2.3-300.fc23.x86_64 kernel-core-4.2.3-300.fc23.x86_64
But there's nothing protecting the kernel-modules* packages

We think that current behavior of dnf-2.3.0 (available from "dnf copr enable rpmsoftwaremanagement/dnf-nightly") is correct. We expect the following behaviors
1. "dnf remove kernel" It should remove all versions on kernel package. kernel package is only metapackage that force to install kernel-core and kernel-modules. But the system doesn't needs it for anything.
2. "dnf remove kernel-modules" It should remove all versions on kernel and kernel-modules packages. Kernel modules provides nice feature for kernel but the system can be run without it (some environment do not install that package at all). And because kernel requires kernel-modules, it will be removed also.
3. "dnf remove kernel-core" Fails due to try to remove also running kernel. It was fixed in dnf-2.x.
4. "dnf upgrade" #with kernel* in transaction Install the new kernel version but removes oldest non running kernel.
Please if you will experience something else from expected behavior, please don't hesitate to reopen the bug report or create the new one.

(2) would be reasonable behaviour if it were guaranteed that all systems could boot without kernel-modules, and that user experience would be largely unaffected.
But it looks to me as if many desktop systems would have problems without kernel-modules: there's enough gpu/network/sound related .kos that users would have a significantly reduced experience without them.
Indeed I see several modules in my initrd that come from the kernel-modules package: /usr/lib/modules/4.10.13-200.fc25.x86_64/kernel/drivers/firmware/iscsi_ibft.ko.xz /usr/lib/modules/4.10.13-200.fc25.x86_64/kernel/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdkfd/amdkfd.ko.xz /usr/lib/modules/4.10.13-200.fc25.x86_64/kernel/drivers/gpu/drm/radeon/radeon.ko.xz /usr/lib/modules/4.10.13-200.fc25.x86_64/kernel/drivers/hid/hid-picolcd.ko.xz /usr/lib/modules/4.10.13-200.fc25.x86_64/kernel/drivers/hid/hid-prodikeys.ko.xz /usr/lib/modules/4.10.13-200.fc25.x86_64/kernel/drivers/hid/hid-sensor-hub.ko.xz /usr/lib/modules/4.10.13-200.fc25.x86_64/kernel/drivers/media/rc/rc-core.ko.xz /usr/lib/modules/4.10.13-200.fc25.x86_64/kernel/drivers/scsi/iscsi_boot_sysfs.ko.xz /usr/lib/modules/4.10.13-200.fc25.x86_64/kernel/sound/core/seq/snd-seq-device.ko.xz /usr/lib/modules/4.10.13-200.fc25.x86_64/kernel/sound/core/snd.ko.xz /usr/lib/modules/4.10.13-200.fc25.x86_64/kernel/sound/core/snd-rawmidi.ko.xz /usr/lib/modules/4.10.13-200.fc25.x86_64/kernel/sound/soundcore.ko.xz
Some of them seem (hid and midi) seem a little weird and don't seem to be loaded, but some (gpu and soundcore) are.

(In reply to Oliver Henshaw from comment #13) > (2) would be reasonable behaviour if it were guaranteed that all systems > could boot without kernel-modules, and that user experience would be largely > unaffected. Unfortunately, this is impossible at this moment and I have doubts it will be possible in near future (like if you will change hardware while computer turned off). > > But it looks to me as if many desktop systems would have problems without > kernel-modules: there's enough gpu/network/sound related .kos that users > would have a significantly reduced experience without them. Well, if you run `dnf remove gdm` you will not be able to run desktop session as well ;) So this is users fault of doing things like this.

(Answered in reverse order, just because)
(In reply to Igor Gnatenko from comment #14) > (In reply to Oliver Henshaw from comment #13) > > But it looks to me as if many desktop systems would have problems without > > kernel-modules: there's enough gpu/network/sound related .kos that users > > would have a significantly reduced experience without them. > Well, if you run `dnf remove gdm` you will not be able to run desktop > session as well ;) So this is users fault of doing things like this. Good point, I guess.
> > (2) would be reasonable behaviour if it were guaranteed that all systems > > could boot without kernel-modules, and that user experience would be largely > > unaffected. > Unfortunately, this is impossible at this moment and I have doubts it will > be possible in near future (like if you will change hardware while computer > turned off). True. There is a rescue kernel+initrd for this case; now I think about it, this rescue image could be used in case a kernel-module removal renders the system unbootable. Downside is still that you wouldn't notice until the next kernel update (and init image rebuild) and that the rescue image would stop working after the next distribution update (i.e. to fedora N+1).
